    <section xml:id="ag-chapter-formatting-architecture">
        <title>Chapter Formatting Architecture</title>
        <introduction>
            <p>In this chapter, we'll lay out the style guide for how chapters that have specific formatting should look, and we'll show you how to write the <init>XML</init> code that will give them this consistent formatting.</p>
        </introduction>
        <subsection>
            <title>Formatting Guide: Discipline<ndash/>Specific Writing</title>
            <introduction>
                <p>This formatting guide focuses specifically on how to make consisitent additions to the <url href="https://soundwriting.pugetsound.edu/discipline-specific-writing.html">Discipline<ndash/>Specific Writing</url> section.</p>
            </introduction>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Overall Structure</title>
                <p>Sections in this chapter are written in close collaboration with faculty members in the department that the section covers. Typically, the student handbook author interviews faculty members and then writes the contents of the section based on what faculty members say in those interviews. A completed draft is presented to the department for approval, and upon receiving approval, it is put into the handbook in its final version.</p>
                <p>Each section begins with a brief introduction about what makes writing in a particular discipline difficult and is followed by a <tag>note</tag> with the following text: <q>Unless otherwise stated, all quotes throughout this section are excerpted from the interview with <fillin/> faculty members that informed this section.</q> The remainder of the section is broken into <tag>paragraphs</tag> titled <q>Genres,</q> <q>Purpose,</q> <q>Traits and Characteristics,</q> <q>Evidence,</q> <q>Conventions and Tips,</q> and <q>Additional Resources.</q> When relevant, the first sentence after the <tag>title</tag> of each paragraph should be a quote by a faculty member excerpted from the informational interview that informed the section. This quote should be in quotation marks (<tag>q</tag>) <em>and</em> italicized with emphasis (<tag>em</tag>).</p>
            </paragraphs>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>Formatting Guide: Writing with Awareness</title>
            <introduction>
                <p>This formatting guide focuses specifically on how to make consisitent additions to the subsections within <url href="https://soundwriting.pugetsound.edu/awareness-inclusive-language.html">Inclusive Language</url>. <url href="https://soundwriting.pugetsound.edu/intersectionality.html">Intersectionality</url> is the framing perspective for the Inclusive Language section, but all subsequent subsections should be titled <q>Language Toward <fillin/> Inclusivity</q> and should contain the internal structure discussed below.</p>
            </introduction>
            <paragraphs xml:id="par-ag-wwa-overview">
                <title>Overview</title>
                <p>Following the <alert>required</alert> introduction (wrap text in a <tag>introduction</tag> tag at the beginning of the subsection), you should describe factual content that you want to impart to readers in a <tag>paragraphs</tag> division with the title <q>Overview.</q> This overview is also <alert>required</alert>, although it can be as long or as short as it needs to be. Additionally, you can include excerpted quotes from Puget Sound students, faculty, or staff in <em>any</em> of the portions of this chapter in an <tag>asssemblage</tag>, which will surround them in a blue box and mark them as external content.</p>
                <p>
                    <assemblage>
                        <title>Staff Perspectives: Musings</title>
                        <blockquote>
                            <p>Typically, it's odd to quote yourself, but I find it empowering to see my own words, written out, as if someone else said them. This seems like as good a place as any to tell everyone that you can see the salaries of the highest<ndash/>paid officials at Puget Sound by looking up the <init>IRS</init> form 990: Schedule J tax form.</p>
                            <attribution>
                                <line>Jordan Fonseca</line>
                                <line>University of Puget Sound</line>
                                <line>June 2019</line>
                            </attribution>
                        </blockquote>
                    </assemblage>
                </p>
                <p>In general, this portion of the subsection should not contain any direct imperatives for the reader (unless they are necessarily embedded in the factual knowledge included) since these instructions will follow in the list of guidelines, or strategies, which is <alert>optional</alert>.</p>
            </paragraphs>
            <list xml:id="list-ag-strategies-for-wwa">
                <title>Strategies for Authoring Additions to <init>WWA</init></title>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p><em>Make the first stenence of each element of this list an imperative.</em></p>
                        <p>If you need to add additional explanation to clarify the instruction above, do so in a separate paragraph (<tag>p</tag> tag) as part of the same list element (<tag>li</tag> tag) below the imperative. These explanations can be several sentences long, if need be, or they can not exist at all. The important part is that the first sentence is (1) an imperative command<mdash/>a strategy and (2) emphasized as important with the <tag>em</tag> tag.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><em>Title the list <q>Strategies for Writing with <fillin/> in Mind</q> to be consistent with how we give guidelines elsewhere in the handbook.</em></p>
                        <p>You would fill in the blank spot with whatever content you filled in the blank spot in the title of the subsection with, so in <q>Writing Toward <em>Racial and Ethnic</em> Inclusivity,</q> the list of guidelines or tips or instructions would be, <q>Strategies for Writing with <em>Racial and Ethnic</em> Inclusivity in Mind.</q></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><em>Create the list by wrapping an unordered list (<tag>ul</tag>) in a list (<tag>list</tag>).</em></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><em>After the list of strategies, insert a list of key terms with the simple title <q>Terms.</q></em></p>
                        <p>The list of terms is, like the list of strategies, <alert>optional</alert>, but if it is included, it must be added as a description list (<tag>dl</tag>) wrapped inside a <tag>list</tag> in which the <term>undefined terms</term> are the <tag>title</tag> of each list item and the phrase completing a sentence beginning with the undefined term (and defining it) follows in the paragraph (<tag>p</tag>) that follows.</p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </list>
            <list>
                <title>Terms</title>
                <dl>
                    <li>
                        <title>undefined terms</title>
                        <p>are words that have not yet been defined</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <title>meta<ndash/>instructions</title>
                        <p>are simultaneously helpful and mind<ndash/>boggling. Definitions of terms need not be restricted to a single sentence, though they should be brief. If extensive discussion is required, the <term>term</term> should probably be discussed in the <xref ref="par-ag-wwa-overview"/>.</p>
                    </li>
                </dl>
            </list>
            <conclusion>
                <p>The last portion of these subsections should be a <tag>conclusion</tag>, which is <alert>optional</alert>, but is a great place to refer readers to additional, relevant resources. We could refer you to an example of what one of these sections actually looks like (check out <url href="https://soundwriting.pugetsound.edu/inclusivity-racial.html">Lanugage Toward Racial and Ethnic Inclusivity</url>), or remind you to read the <url href="https://pretextbook.org/doc/author-guide/html/"><pretext/> Author's Guide</url>.</p>
            </conclusion>
        </subsection>
    </section>
